This is a straightforward application of Simpson's Rule to the integral

\begin{align*}V = \int_{0}^{60}A(y)\,dy.\end{align*}

Notice that

$\frac{\Delta x}{3} = \frac{\tfrac{60-0}{6}}{3} = \frac{10}{3}$

By Simpson's Rule, the integral can be approximated by the sum

\begin{align*}
V \approx \frac{10}{3}(A(0) + 4A(10) + 2A(20) + 4A(30) + 2A(40) + 4A(50) + A(60))\end{align*} Remembering the given information about the diameter
$D(y)$ of the tree trunk at various heights, $y$, we make the
appropriate substitutions to determine the cross sectional area at each
height:

\begin{align*}A(y) = \pi \left(\frac{D(y)}{2}\right)^2 = \frac{\pi}{4}D(y)^{2}\end{align*}

Plugging into our sum we get the approximate volume for the tree trunk.

\begin{align*}
V &\approx \frac{10\pi}{12}(10^2 + 4\times 8^2 + 2\times 7^2 + 4\times 6^2  + 2\times 5^2 + 4\times 4^2 + 3^2)\end{align*}
